### What is Change Detection?

Change detection is the mechanism Angular uses to keep the template in sync with the component class. Angular checks the component tree for changes and updates the DOM accordingly.

### Default Strategy

By default, Angular uses **ChangeDetectionStrategy.Default**. On every asynchronous event (click, XHR response, setTimeout), Angular walks the entire component tree and checks every binding for changes.

### OnPush Strategy

`ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush` optimizes change detection by checking a component only when:

1. **@Input() references change** (new object reference — mutating properties does NOT trigger)
2. **An event originates from the component or its children** (click, keyup, etc.)
3. **An Observable bound with AsyncPipe emits**
4. **ChangeDetectorRef.markForCheck() is called explicitly**

```typescript
import { ChangeDetectionStrategy, Component } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-user',
  template: `<p>{{ user.name }}</p>`,
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  standalone: true
})
export class UserComponent {
  @Input() user: User;
}
```

### ChangeDetectorRef

`ChangeDetectorRef` provides programmatic control:

```typescript
import { ChangeDetectorRef, Component } from '@angular/core';

@Component({...})
export class DataComponent {
  constructor(private cdr: ChangeDetectorRef) {}

  loadData() {
    this.dataService.getData().subscribe(data => {
      this.data = data;
      this.cdr.markForCheck();     // Schedule change detection
      // this.cdr.detectChanges(); // Run change detection immediately
    });
  }

  stopChecking() {
    this.cdr.detach();             // Detach from change detection tree
  }

  resumeChecking() {
    this.cdr.reattach();           // Reattach to change detection tree
  }
}
```

### Zone.js and NgZone

Angular uses **Zone.js** to monkey-patch browser async APIs (setTimeout, addEventListener, XHR). When a task completes, Zone.js notifies Angular to run change detection.

You can optimize with `NgZone`:

```typescript
constructor(private ngZone: NgZone) {}

runOutsideAngular() {
  this.ngZone.runOutsideAngular(() => {
    setInterval(() => {
      // This interval does NOT trigger change detection
      console.log('Running outside Angular zone');
    }, 1000);
  });
}

runInsideAngular() {
  this.ngZone.run(() => {
    // Explicitly run change detection inside Angular
  });
}
```

### Signals-Based Change Detection

With Angular signals, change detection becomes **fine-grained**. When a signal value changes, only the components using that signal are marked for update:

```typescript
@Component({
  changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush,
  template: `<p>{{ count() }}</p>`
})
export class CounterComponent {
  count = signal(0);

  increment() {
    this.count.update(v => v + 1);
    // No manual markForCheck needed — signal updates the view automatically
  }
}
```

### Summary

| Strategy | Description | Use Case |
|----------|-------------|----------|
| `Default` | Check all components on every async event | Small apps, simple components |
| `OnPush` | Check only when inputs change or events fire | Performance-sensitive, pure components |
| `Detach` | Manual control via ChangeDetectorRef | Specialized optimization |
| Signals | Granular, signal-driven updates | New Angular apps (16+) |

